BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Ucdavis Library": "https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/copy-of-datalab-office-hours-in-person"}
X-SOURCE-ID:ucdavis_library
SUMMARY:DataLab Office Hours (in person)
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260310T200000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260310T210000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50755967516358
DESCRIPTION:DataLab offers free in person drop-in office hours during whic
 h UC Davis researchers can obtain data science help and advice on working 
 with their data. During these short\, just-in-time sessions we meet with f
 aculty\, students\, postdoctoral scholars\, and staff from all domains acr
 oss the University. Depending on the nature of your question and our avail
 ability\, it may be possible to schedule a longer follow-up consultation a
 fter your office hours visit.\n\nAppointments are not required. Please com
 plete the brief office hours intake form ahead of time to help us connect 
 you with the right expert for your question.\n\nCommon office hours help t
 opics include:\n\nOpen Source Programming (R\, Python\, Julia\, etc.)Repro
 ducible research computing and data scienceResponsible and ethical data sc
 ienceData gathering\, organization\, databases\, and experimental designDa
 ta analysis\, statistics\, and explorationData visualizationMachine learni
 ng and neural networksText mining and natural language processingGeospatia
 l sciencesRemote and high performance computingComputational pedagogy… a
 nd more!Please note that drop-in office hours are not offered during Unive
 rsity holidays\, academic breaks and finals week. Summer schedule varies. 
 DataLab may only be accessed during Shields Library's business hours. Clic
 k here for detailed directions to DataLab.\n\nNote: We are unable to provi
 de support for assigned coursework (homework assignments\, class projects\
 , etc.) during office hours. If you need such help please contact your ins
 tructor or TA for assistance. If you need help with technical problems suc
 h system administration and hardware issues\, check out the the UC Davis S
 erviceHub and/or contact your departmental IT.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 360
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/copy-of-datalab-office-hours-
 in-person
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Ucdavis Library": "https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/davis-python-users-group-w26"}
X-SOURCE-ID:ucdavis_library
SUMMARY:Davis Python Users Group
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260310T220000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260310T230000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51825975222552
DESCRIPTION:The Davis Python Users Group (DPUG) is a friendly meetup where
  community members\, including DataLab staff\, discuss their experiences\,
  discoveries\, and questions about using the Python programming language a
 nd about research computing in general.\n\n \n\nMost DPUG meetings are inf
 ormal “studio” sessions\, which may begin with a short presentation (1
 5-20 minutes) to prompt discussion. You’re encouraged to share your pers
 pectives\, bring your own questions\, or just pull up a virtual seat and c
 ode along. Studio meetings are generally hybrid (in-person and over Zoom) 
 and do not require advance registration. Zoom links are distributed throug
 h our mailing list a few days in advance.\n\n \n\nSee our website for more
  details and how to signup to our mailing list.
LOCATION:Shields Library\, 362
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/davis-python-users-group-w26
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Ucdavis Library": "https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/covered-faculty-author-talks-march2026"}
X-SOURCE-ID:ucdavis_library
SUMMARY:Covered: Faculty Author Talks by Emily Klancher Merchant\, Talinn 
 Grigor & Houri Berberian
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260311T003000Z
DTEND;VALUE=DATE-TIME:20260311T023000Z
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_51817231960329
DESCRIPTION:Join us for an evening with UC Davis faculty authors Emily Kla
 ncher Merchant and Talinn Grigor\, and UC Irvine faculty author Houri Berb
 erian as part of Covered\, a monthly event series celebrating recent books
  from the College of Letters and Science.\n \n\nEmily Klancher Merchant\, 
 associate professor of Science and Technology Studies\, discusses DNA\, Ra
 ce\, and Reproduction\, an interdisciplinary volume exploring how genomic 
 ideas shape racial identity and reproductive decision-making.\n Talinn Gri
 gor\, professor of art history\, and Houri Berberian\, professor of histor
 y and director of the Center for Armenian Studies at UC Irvine\, share ins
 ights from The Armenian Woman\, which traces Armenian women’s cultural\,
  political and intellectual influence on Iranian modernity.  \n\n\n\n\nCov
 ered: Spotlighting Faculty Authors in Letters and Science is co-sponsored 
 by the Jan Shrem and Maria Manetti Shrem Museum and the UC Davis Library.
LOCATION:Manetti Shrem Museum
URL:https://events.library.ucdavis.edu/event/covered-faculty-author-talks-
 march2026
X-SOURCE:UC Davis Library
END:VEVENT
